column3: Canada West Coast - Woodfibre Creek Delta Failure
column10: In 1955 a failure of the delta slope at Woodfibre Creek was triggered by an extreme low tide.

column3: Canada West Coast - Fraser River Delta Failure
column10: The Fraser River Delta is the largest delta in western Canada. In 1985 a large mass wasting event moved approximately 3*10^6 cubic meters of material. The region of Tsawwassen and Deltas population combine to be about 101000 is an area of explosive urban and industrial growth.

column3: Canada West Coast - Kitimat Arm Failure 1975
column10: Two slides in the area have created tsunamis, one in 1974 and in 1975. The 1975 slide was likely triggered by a combination of low tides and construction. At least 26000000 m^3 of sediment was moved.

St Lawrence - Betsiamites - Lower St. Lawrence
column10: Three 3 main events (7250 cal BP, AD 1663, and AD 1860 or 1870) of slope instability where identified within the 70km2 area of this study region. The 1663 AD Failure - With many failures along the St. Lawrence and its fjords this one stands out having an area of 6.5 km^2 over 3 million m^3 this is one of the largest submarine slides in Quebec. It was likely triggered by the 1663 earthquake of magnitude M=~7. The 1663 submarine debris flow failure is associated with a subaerial landslide observed onshore.

column3: Canada East Coast - Grand Banks Failure
column10: 1929 - Triggered by a M=7.2 earthquake the slope failure created a devastating tsunami which was observed on the Atlantic coast of Canada and USA and as far east as Portugal and the Azores Islands.

column3: Canada East Coast - Hopedale-Makkovik Failure Complex
column10: A series of MTD's containing large slabs up to 6 km across. Deposits of the complex cover an area greater than 28000km^2 .
